AGI - "O give me the money or I'll leave you." The 'sentimental' extortion for the Cassation is crime in the case of the story of a woman from Rovigo who denounced the companion by attaching the screen shots of the messages from which there emerged axious demands of money with threats, including that of truncating the relationship.&nbsp; "Even the intimation of the breakup of a sentimental relationship can well assume threatening value - write the judges of the Supreme Court in the judgment read by the AGI and diffused by the Studio Cataldi - when, far from representing the manifestation of its own free choice, constitutes an expression of blackmail". The 'ermellini' have therefore confirmed the sentence already pronounced by the gup of Rovigo.
&nbsp;
Dismissed the thesis of man's lawyers who tried to argue that the demands for money had occurred in the context of "their consensual menage characterized by strong verbal violence but never co-artated with the consequence that every act carried out by the woman was to be considered fully fruit of her free determinations. The circumstances of the fact, including the methods of payment all traceable and the fact that the defendant had been activated for the return, excluded that the offence could be considered a particularly vulnerable subject.
&nbsp;
Neither the extortionive threat could be seen in the prospect of a sentimental break without the connotation of affective blackmail, however, of the affirmed intent of the woman to get away from the defendant." But for the Cassation it is a question of extortion considering "the existence of a psychological prevarication and subditance with requests for advanced money with aggressive or threatening tones but also larvae and subdule".

